| National Projects Aim to Reboot the Internet                       |
|   from the do-it-right-this-time dept.                             |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday April 13, @21:09 (Networking)           |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/13/2130206     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

iron-kurton wrote with a link to an AP story about a national initiative
to [0]scrap the internet and start over. You may remember our discussion
last month about [1]Stanford's Clean Slate Design project; this article
details similar projects across the country, all with the federal
government's blessing and all with the end goal of revamping our current
networking system. From the article: "No longer constrained by slow
connections and computer processors and high costs for storage,
researchers say the time has come to rethink the Internet's underlying
architecture, a move that could mean replacing networking equipment and
rewriting software on computers to better channel future traffic over the
existing pipes. Even Vinton Cerf, one of the Internet's founding fathers
as co-developer of the key communications techniques, said the exercise
was 'generally healthy' because the current technology 'does not satisfy
all needs.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/13/2130206

Links:
    0. http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070413/ap_on_hi_te/rebuilding_the_internet
    1. http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/03/15/1830217&tid=95


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Shaking a 275-ton Building                                         |
|   from the without-using-your-superpowers dept.                    |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday April 14, @01:11 (Supercomputing)     |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/14/0512244      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Roland Piquepaille writes "If you want to predict how a tall building
can resist to an earthquake, some researchers have better tools than
others. Engineers from the San Diego Supercomputer Center (SDSC) have
built a full-size 275-ton building and really shaken it to obtain
[1]earthshaking images. The building was equipped with some 600 sensors
and filmed as the shake table simulated the 1994 Northridge earthquake in
Los Angeles, California. It gave so much data to the engineers to analyze
that they needed a supercomputer to help them. Now they hope their study
will yield to better structure performance for future buildings in case
of earthquakes."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/14/0512244

Links:
    0. http://www.primidi.com/
    1. http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2007-04/uocei041107.php


