| Jon Stewart, Lorne Michaels Come Out In Favour of YouTube          |
|   from the somebody-has-to-right dept.                             |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday April 14, @03:14 (Google)             |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/14/0521209              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

techdirt writes "Viacom employee Jon Stewart recently announced that he
[0]believes his bosses are making a mistake in taking Viacom content off
of YouTube. Today, NBC employee and Saturday Night Live creator Lorne
Michaels has stated he [1]can't understand NBC's position on YouTube. The
interview with Michaels is especially interesting, because it was a
Saturday Night Live clip of the infamous 'Lazy Sunday' music video that
is often credited with putting YouTube on the map. At the same time,
however, almost everyone admitted that it did wonders in revitalizing
SNL's reputation (as well as boosting Andy Samberg's reputation to new
heights). Yet, NBC's lawyers [2]shot it down, limiting the benefit to
SNL. It appears that Michaels understands that, and says [3]he wishes
they could put more of the show on YouTube."

